# Data Provider Pattern

## Data Provider Pattern
- Abstract data access behind `DataProvider` interface in `src/lib/dataProvider.ts`.
- Implement concrete adapters (e.g., `LocalAdapter`) that implement the interface.
- Use Context API (`DataContext`) to provide data access throughout app.
- Custom hooks (`useCheckins`, `useWeekly`, `useGoals`) wrap context for convenience.

## Local Storage
- All localStorage keys prefixed with `arix_` and versioned (e.g., `arix_local_checkins_v01`).
- Use helper functions `readLS<T>()` and `writeLS<T>()` with try-catch for safety.
- Validate data on read/write; provide sensible defaults.
- Version keys to enable future migrations.

## Data Structures
- Define TypeScript interfaces in `src/lib/types.ts` for all data models.
- Use `Modality` union types for constrained values.
- Date handling: use `toYMD()` helper for YYYY-MM-DD format.
- Week calculations: use `startOfWeek()` helper with consistent week start day.

## Business Logic
- Keep computation logic in adapter classes (e.g., `computeWeeklyRollup`).
- Validation functions (e.g., `validateCheckin`) enforce data integrity.
- Constants for business rules (e.g., `MODALITY_FACTOR`, `DURATIONS`) in adapter files.
- Separate data access from UI components.

## Do
- Use the DataProvider interface for all data operations.
- Version localStorage keys for future migrations.
- Validate data before saving.
- Keep business logic in data layer, not components.

## Don't
- Access localStorage directly from components.
- Hardcode localStorage keys; use constants.
- Mix data access with UI logic.
- Skip validation on user input.
- Use unversioned storage keys.

